subSubSection.paragraph:
Description.
Colony encrusting, unilaminar, multiserial. Autozooids oval to rectangular (ZL 474±47, 406–596, 20; ZW 288±26, 255–356, 20), arranged in irregular series, zooids separated by shallow grooves (
Fig. 2A–D
), whitish translucent when dried. Vertical walls with two or more uniporous pore plates per neighbouring zooid. Development of gymnocyst reduced to proximal region and distolateral corner(s), cryptocyst a narrow band with a nodular surface, opesia extensive (OpL 372±30, 318–445, 20; OpW 205±15, 180–230, 20) (
Fig. 2A, C, D
). Opercular region laterally with a pair of cylindrical to slightly flattened oral spines, more or less directing terminally (
Fig. 2C–E
); frontal membrane in mature zooids overarched by 6–9 cylindrical mural spines that slightly thin towards their tips while not reaching the zooidal mid-line, proximal spines shorter (
Fig. 2A–D
); all spines apparently unjointed at their base.

Ovicell usually endozooidal in distal avicularium but often in distal autozooid (
Fig. 2B, D
), ooecium continuous with the gymnocyst of the avicularian or autozooidal cystid forming a short but broad hemispherical cap (OvL 89±13, 67–115, 20; OvW 182±17, 154–213, 20), entire proximal margin slightly raised but without a distinctive peak (
Fig. 2B, D, E
).

Avicularia interzooidal, distal to many zooids (
Fig. 3A–D
), particularly abundant in fertile colony regions, usually pointing distolaterally but often laterally, distally or even proximally, distinctly longer than wide and oval in outline, widest proximal to condyles, (AL 171±19, 140–213, 20; AW 112±7, 101–128, 20); rostrum semielliptical or rounded-triangular, occasionally with relatively pointed tip (
Fig. 2D
), rostrum at an acute angle to colony surface, mandible hinged on a pair of short triangular condyles delimiting an approximately semicircular proximal area with an immersed calcified shelf (ML 97±12, 77–117, 20; MW 98±6, 87–110, 20), interior mandible with a large central oval lucida (
Fig. 2C
); gymnocyst usually reduced to cystid corners, occasionally better developed all around.
